in_class_description_detail: Any soft-bottom area dominated by fine unconsolidated sediments
Comment: Think we need to revisit how we deal with sand in these CR datasets

in_class_description_detail: Any habitat featuring loose, rough fragments of broken reef material.
efg_description: These slow growing biogenic structures are formed by the calcium carbonate skeletons of certain coral species that depend on symbiotic relationships with algae. They occur in warm, shallow, low-nutrient waters and provide complex three-dimensional habitat for a highly diverse community across all trophic levels, from algae to sharks, along with other characteristic sessile organisms like coralline algae and sponges. Niche habitats produce specialist behaviours and diets, like the symbiotic relationship between clown fish and anemones. Storms and marine heat waves drive cycles of reef destruction and renewal.
